      <details>
        <summary>Are stocks priced under $10 inherently a good, cheap investment?</summary>
        <p>Absolutely not. A stock's nominal sticker price alone does absolutely nothing to determine if it is actually a good, fundamentally sound investment. You must look strictly at the company's total market capitalization, its current earnings, its debt load, and its realistic future prospects. The vast majority of stocks trading under $10 are incredibly cheap for a very specific, usually terrible reason (poor fundamentals, massive debt, or dying industries).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the specific legal difference between a standard $10 stock and a 'penny stock'?</summary>
        <p>The US Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) officially defines a 'penny stock' as any stock trading significantly under $5.00 per share that is absolutely not listed on a major, regulated national exchange. Therefore, a legitimate stock trading at $10 on the NASDAQ is definitely not a penny stock, but it is still broadly considered a highly volatile, low-priced stock by institutional investors.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is it mathematically easier for a $5 stock to double to $10 than a $50 stock to double to $100?</summary>
